Histologic lesions are characterized by severe pyogranulomatous inflammation and are most commonly observed in the mesentery and along the peritoneal surface. Pyogranulomatous inflammation commonly encompasses the small intestine and focally expands or destroys the muscularis and serosa (Fig. 4
). Pyogranulomas are characterized by central areas of necrosis composed of cellular debris and degenerative neutrophils surrounded by epithelioid macrophages with additional layers of lymphocytes and plasma cells (Fig. 5
). Rare multinucleated giant cells have been described.
